<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<entry xmlns:functx="http://www.functx.com" xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="entry_kʼæʒ"
    xml:lang="os">
    <form xml:lang="os-x-iron" type="lemma">
        <orth>kʼæʒ</orth>
    </form>
    <form xml:lang="os-x-digor" type="dialectal">
        <orth>kʼæʒæ</orth>
    </form>
    <sense>
        <cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
            <q>кривой</q>
        </cit>
        <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
            <q>crooked</q>
        </cit>
    </sense>
    <re>
        <re>
            <form type="lemma">
                <orth>kʼæʒ kænyn</orth>
            </form>
            <sense>
                <cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
                    <q>сгибать</q>
                </cit>
                <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                    <q>bend</q>
                </cit>
            </sense>
        </re>
        <re>
            <form type="lemma">
                <orth>kʼæʒ-mæʒ</orth>
            </form>
            <sense>
                <cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
                    <q>криво и косо</q>
                </cit>
                <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                    <q>crooked and askew</q>
                </cit>
            </sense>
        </re>
    </re>
    <etym xml:lang="ru">Очевидна связь с <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/><w>kāz,
        kaj</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="xpr"
            ><lang/><w>kž-</w><gloss><q>кривой</q></gloss></mentioned>
                (<bibl><author>Henning</author><ref target="#ref_BSOS"/><biblScope>IX
            84</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/><w>kaj-maj</w></mentioned> = ос.
            <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kʼæʒ-mæʒ"/>. Трудно сказать, имеем ли дело с исконным
        родством или заимствованием. Перебойным вариантом данного слова является <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_xæʒ"/>. Может быть, сюда же <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kʼæʒīl"/>
                ‘хвост’.%n<bibl><ref target="#ref_Bailey._Asica"
        /><biblScope>30</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
    <etym xml:lang="en">The connection with <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/><w>kāz,
            kaj</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="xpr"
                ><lang/><w>kž-</w><gloss><q>crooked</q></gloss></mentioned> is evident
                (<bibl><author>Henning</author><ref target="#ref_BSOS"/><biblScope>IX
            84</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/><w>kaj-maj</w></mentioned> =
        Ossetic <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kʼæʒ-mæʒ"/>. It is difficult to say whether it is the
        congation or the borrowing. The irregularly corresponding variant of this word is <ref
            type="xr" target="#entry_xæʒ"/>. Maybe, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kʼæʒīl"/> ‘tail’
        is related to it as well.%n<bibl><ref target="#ref_Bailey._Asica"
            /><biblScope>30</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
    <note type="internal">перебойный вариант??</note>
</entry>
